Gauteng public healthcare facilities delivered 150 babies between midnight and 12:00 on 1 January. The MEC for health, Nomathemba Mokgethi, visited Rahima Moosa Mother and Child Hospital in Johannesburg to welcome some of the babies, celebrate with the parents and to present some gifts. According to the MEC's spokesperson, Kwara Kekana, academic hospitals delivered 29 babies. Tertiary hospitals delivered 19 babies - Kalafong Hospital delivered eight and Tembisa Hospital 11. While visiting the new baby mothers, Mokgethi stressed that Covid-19 still existed and advised all pregnant and breastfeeding women to get vaccinated to protect themselves and their families from severe illness. "I want to take this opportunity to wish a happy and prosperous new year to all parents who welcomed their babies," said Mokgethi. The Western Cape health department spokesperson, Maret Lesch, told News24 they would be releasing a statement on Sunday to reveal the number of babies born on New Year's Day.